2. 🧩 Define the container architecture for Trixxie v1

Your agent platform is basically a small constellation of services. The minimal v1 constellation usually includes:

    gateway — FastAPI or similar, handles requests

    agent-core — your runtime logic, memory, tools

    vectorstore — SQLite, Qdrant, or DuckDB (local, simple)

    task-runner — background jobs, scheduled tasks

    proxy — Caddy or Traefik for TLS + routing

For Podman, the cleanest approach is a pod:
Code

podman pod create --name agentcore-pod -p 80:80 -p 443:443

Then each service runs inside the pod with shared networking.

This gives you:

    unified logs

    unified lifecycle

    no daemon

    SELinux‑friendly isolation

    systemd integration that “just works”

3. ⚙️ Prepare systemd units for 24/7 hosting

This is where your platform becomes a service, not just a container.

A typical unit for the gateway might look like:
Code

[Unit]
Description=AgentCore Gateway
Wants=network-online.target
After=network-online.target

[Service]
Restart=always
ExecStart=/usr/bin/podman run --rm \
  --pod AgentCore-pod \
  -v /srv/AgentCore/config:/app/config:Z \
  -v /srv/AgentCore/data:/app/data:Z \
  AgentCore-gateway:latest

[Install]
WantedBy=multi-user.target

You’ll have one unit per container, or a single unit that starts the entire pod.

This gives you:

    automatic restart

    clean shutdown

    journald logs

    predictable boot behavior

